<h2 id="heading-0">The Manual Bookkeeping Trap</h2>

<p>Texas business owners spend an average of 12 hours per month on bookkeeping. That's 144 hours per year - the equivalent of 3.5 weeks of full-time work.</p>

<p>Most of that time is wasted on repetitive tasks that computers should do. Data entry. Reconciling accounts. Categorizing transactions. Chasing receipts.</p>

<p>After automating bookkeeping for 150+ Texas businesses, I've found that 80% of bookkeeping tasks can be automated. The key is knowing what to automate first.</p>

<p>Here's the automation roadmap that saves Texas businesses the most time and money.</p>

<h2 id="heading-1">Level 1: Transaction Import (Save 4 hours/month)</h2>

<h3 id="heading-2">Bank Feed Automation</h3>

<p><strong>What it does:</strong> Automatically imports bank and credit card transactions into your accounting software.</p>

<p><strong>Texas banks that work:</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Chase, Bank of America, Wells Fargo</li>
<li>Texas Capital Bank, Frost Bank</li>
<li>All major credit card processors</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Setup time:</strong> 30 minutes</p>

<p><strong>Monthly time savings:</strong> 2-3 hours of manual data entry</p>

<h3 id="heading-3">How to Set It Up</h3>

<ol>
<li>Connect your bank accounts in QuickBooks/Xero</li>
<li>Review imported transactions weekly</li>
<li>Set up rules for automatic categorization</li>
<li>Reconcile monthly as backup</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="heading-4">Texas Tip</h3>

<p>Texas businesses with multiple bank accounts (checking, savings, credit cards) save the most time here.</p>

